Someone with more experience with this may correct me, but I believe what you can do is randomly divide all your products into two categories. In one category you keep the price the same. In the other category you raise the price by e.g. 10%.
If, after running the A/B test the proportion of revenue coming from the products where you raised the prices goes with, and it's statistically significant, you keep the new price.

messages.content: could someone help me with the difference between backbones & architectures in DL? i'm going through the paper "ForestNet: Classifying Drivers of Deforestation in Indonesia using Deep Learning on Satellite Imagery" right now & can't figure out the difference between the two
probably way out of my depth but i'm trying to implement this paper so any high-level explanations/resources about what integrating the backbone & architecture would be really appreciated!!

FPNs and U-Nets are very similar. Tho the paper says they tried both, it doesn't seem (at least from skimming) that they bothered to remark on how they stacked up relatively. Since other 2% differences warranted mention I'm guessing the variation was less than that. Also unsure why they didn't use HRNet, which is simpler than FPN while (far as i know) kicking its ass.

They also used DeepLab. For DeepLab, the "backbone" is basically everything in the network before a final set of "classifier" modules and/or things like CRF. E.g. most of the network. DeepLab just takes that backbone, which usually downsamples the input a few times, tacks some stuff on, and you get a segmentation map out that you then "upsample" to the proper size

With FPNs / UNets, the backbone is just the encoder; after that, you have a decoder that upsamples the volume back to the original size.

Think of FPN/UNet as an hourglass of convolutions, and DeepLab as just like a stretched-out first half of an hourglass with the pointy end cut off lol

So the quickest path to implementation is probably just starting with the vanilla DeepLab repo. If you Really want to use EfficientNet over something like ResNet, there are some nice example repos to look at e.g.
https://github.com/zhoudaxia233/EfficientUnet

I guess to better answer your original question:
- an architecture is a way of assembling deep-learning computational units (layers, activations, etc.)
- a backbone is a common architecture often used as a starting point / foundation for another architecture.

E.g.: ResNet-101 is on its own a big ol' classification architecture. But it is also a "backbone" for the DeepLab architecture, because it serves as the starting point

**long explanation incoming:** So paraglide is pretty different from any tools that exist right now / anything I've seen. It stems from the observation that nobody really wants to use these no-code autoML tools because of a bunch of reasons (abstraction, no customization, horrible in production etc.). The idea behind paraglide is that we're providing layers to the whole ML pipeline. If you're an extremely non-technical user you can just specify the dataset, and the target column and let us handle it.

If you're a bit more advanced you can work with the grammar built into paraglide, for this think natural language representations of machine learning tasks like for example "one-hot" representing one-hot-encoding. If you're a data scientist you can go in, code up your custom modules, and then include within the pipeline. OR you can do all of that in one workflow!

Let's say you're a data engineer but don't really have experience with modeling etc, you can build your custom modules for the preprocessing step, analysis step and let paraglide handle everything in between / around it. In ANY other ML tool you're stuck with the choice between either having to start from scratch, use 8 different tools to do each step, or work completely hands off. It's really an ML infrastructure tool with AutoML components rather than just an AutoML tool.
